$\begin{align}
f_x(3, 6) &= \dfrac{1}{2 \sqrt{x + y}} = \dfrac{1}{2\sqrt{9}} = \dfrac{1}{6} \\ \\
f_y(3, 6) &= \dfrac{1}{2 \sqrt{x + y}} = \dfrac{1}{2\sqrt{9}} = \dfrac{1}{6}
\end{align}$

Let's find $f_x$, $f_y$, and $f_z$. We can find $f_x$ by using the chain rule, treating $yz$ as if it were a constant.

[[☃ explanation 1]]

$\begin{align}
f_x &= \dfrac{\partial}{\partial x} \left[ \tan(xyz) \right] \\ \\
&= yz \cdot \dfrac{1}{\cos^2(xyz)}
\end{align}$

The other two are similar, just replacing the variables that we treat as constant.

$\begin{align}
f_y &= xz \cdot \dfrac{1}{\cos^2(xyz)} \\ \\
f_z &= xy \cdot \dfrac{1}{\cos^2(xyz)}
\end{align}$
